# Hibernate – Quick Revision Notes

## 1. What is Hibernate

Hibernate is an Object Relational Mapping (ORM) framework for Java that simplifies interaction between Java applications and relational databases.

ORM maps Java objects to database tables so developers can work with objects instead of writing SQL queries manually.

Example mapping:

Java class

```
@Entity
public class student {
    @Id
    int rollNo;
    String name;
}
```

Database table

```
student
--------
rollNo
name
```

Hibernate automatically converts Java object operations into SQL queries.

---

## 2. Why Hibernate is Used

Problems with JDBC:

* Requires writing SQL queries manually
* Large amount of boilerplate code
* Manual mapping between objects and tables
* Harder to maintain in large systems

Hibernate advantages:

* Automatic SQL generation
* Object-oriented database interaction
* Reduced code complexity
* Built-in caching support
* Database independence

---

## 3. JDBC vs Hibernate

| Feature                  | JDBC          | Hibernate                |
| ------------------------ | ------------- | ------------------------ |
| Query writing            | Manual SQL    | Automatic SQL generation |
| Code size                | Large         | Smaller                  |
| Mapping                  | Manual        | Automatic                |
| Performance optimization | Manual        | Built-in features        |
| Caching                  | Not available | Available                |
| Maintenance              | Harder        | Easier                   |

Example:

JDBC

```
PreparedStatement ps =
con.prepareStatement("insert into student values(?,?,?)");
```

Hibernate

```
session.persist(student);
```

Hibernate internally converts object operations into SQL queries.

---

## 4. How Hibernate Works

Architecture flow:

```
Java Application
       ↓
Hibernate Framework
       ↓
JDBC
       ↓
Database (PostgreSQL / MySQL / etc.)
```

Hibernate internally uses JDBC but hides its complexity.

---

## 5. Hibernate Architecture

Main components:

```
Application
     ↓
Configuration
     ↓
SessionFactory
     ↓
Session
     ↓
Transaction
     ↓
Database
```

Each component has a specific role in managing database interaction.

---

## 6. Important Hibernate Terms

### Entity

An entity is a Java class mapped to a database table.

```
@Entity
public class student
```

### SessionFactory

A heavy object responsible for creating sessions.
Created once for the entire application.

```
SessionFactory sf = cfg.buildSessionFactory();
```

### Session

Represents a connection between the application and the database.

```
Session session = sf.openSession();
```

Used for performing operations like:

* Insert
* Update
* Delete
* Fetch

### Transaction

Ensures that database operations are executed safely and consistently.

```
session.beginTransaction();
session.persist(student);
session.getTransaction().commit();
```

Without a transaction, database changes may not be saved properly.

---

## 7. Basic Hibernate Operations (CRUD)

Insert

```
session.persist(student);
```

Fetch

```
student s = session.get(student.class, 101);
```

Update

```
student s = session.get(student.class,101);
s.setsName("Updated");
session.update(s);
```

Delete

```
student s = session.get(student.class,101);
session.remove(s);
```

---

## 8. Changing Table or Column Name

Sometimes the class name and table name are different.

Table mapping:

```
@Entity
@Table(name="student_table")
```

Column mapping:

```
@Column(name="student_name")
private String name;
```

---

## 9. Embeddable Mapping

Used when one class is embedded inside another entity.

Example: Address inside Student.

```
@Embeddable
class Address {
   String city;
   String state;
}
```

Inside the entity:

```
@Embedded
Address address;
```

---

## 10. Relationship Mapping

Used when tables are related to each other.

### One-to-One

Example: Person ↔ Passport

```
@OneToOne
Passport passport;
```

### One-to-Many

Example: Department → Employees

```
@OneToMany
List<Employee> employees;
```

### Many-to-One

Example: Many students belong to one department

```
@ManyToOne
Department dept;
```

### Many-to-Many

Example: Students ↔ Courses

```
@ManyToMany
List<Course> courses;
```

Hibernate automatically creates a join table for many-to-many relationships.

---

## 11. Lazy vs Eager Fetch

### Lazy Fetch

Data is loaded only when it is needed.

Example:
Student loads first
Courses load later when accessed

Improves performance.

### Eager Fetch

All related data loads immediately.

Example:
Student and courses load together.

Can reduce performance for large datasets.

---

## 12. Hibernate Caching

Hibernate supports two levels of caching.

### First-Level Cache

Default cache at the session level.

```
Session → Cache → Database
```

Prevents repeated database queries in the same session.

### Second-Level Cache

Shared cache across multiple sessions.

Common implementation:
Ehcache

Helps improve performance by reducing database access.

---

## 13. Fetching Specific Properties

Instead of retrieving the entire object, specific fields can be fetched.

Example SQL:

```
SELECT name FROM student
```

Using Hibernate Query Language (HQL):

```
Query q = session.createQuery("select sName from student");
```

---

## 14. HQL vs SQL

| Feature  | SQL                   | HQL             |
| -------- | --------------------- | --------------- |
| Works on | Database tables       | Java classes    |
| Syntax   | Database specific     | Object-oriented |
| Example  | SELECT * FROM student | FROM student    |

---

## 15. Indexing (SQL Concept)

Indexes improve database query performance.

Example:

```
CREATE INDEX idx_name ON student(name);
```

Indexes help speed up searches in large datasets.

---

## 16. Where Hibernate is Used

Hibernate is commonly used in backend applications built with Java.

Typical backend stack:

```
Spring Boot
     ↓
Hibernate / JPA
     ↓
Database
```

Hibernate simplifies database interaction in large-scale enterprise applications.

